      "text": "\nParadoxes make for fun thought experiments, but are logically and physically impossible. Chances are that [[Time Travel]] is possible (at least, we have no reason to believe it impossible due to the [[Space Time]] relationship), but it is our intuition of cause and effect that is problematic. If quantum physics and the matter-wave relationship holds, it is also quite possible that time travel to the past will actually involve travel to alternative histories and that we beings of matter can only experience a small fraction of the spatial-temporal universe that follows many paths, strengthening some and destroying others.  (If so, other versions of us are experiencing the small fraction of the other possibilities in which we were born and somehow remain alive.) If you go into the past to kill your Grandfather, perhaps you'll succeed in a senseless murder then end up in prison (without a legal identity) in the alternative history, while friends and family from your original path will simply wonder where (and when!) you went.",
